snippet.textDisplay:
In my first year of college, a student from my Spanish class who I'd spoken to maybe 4 times asked me to act in a scene he had to direct, to be presented live to his theater instructor for his final project. He said it didn't matter that I had no prior acting experience. He emailed me the script and arranged a rehearsal. I thought rehearsal meant we sit down together, read the script, and the director teaches us how to deliver our lines. No. He wanted me to memorize it in the few days before. Wow. Never mentioned that. So I come to rehearsal completely unprepared, reading my lines from paper.

The group using the practice room before us ran late and had the door locked. Then we got kicked out early because an instructor came by and said schedule be damned, he needed to use the room.

The director couldn't / wouldn't schedule another practice. I said I wasn't comfortable doing the job without more practice. He told me there was nobody else to do the part, and I would just have to do my best.

Presentation day. I get my first 2 lines out and then I couldn't remember a damn thing more. Had no idea what the play was even about or what my lines meant so I couldn't even fake it. After I missed my line, nobody else could remember theirs either. The director wasn't allowed to help. So we all just stood there paralyzed and embarrassed until the instructor called it a wash.

I assume he got a pretty bad grade because he never spoke to me again.
snippet.textOriginal:
In my first year of college, a student from my Spanish class who I'd spoken to maybe 4 times asked me to act in a scene he had to direct, to be presented live to his theater instructor for his final project. He said it didn't matter that I had no prior acting experience. He emailed me the script and arranged a rehearsal. I thought rehearsal meant we sit down together, read the script, and the director teaches us how to deliver our lines. No. He wanted me to memorize it in the few days before. Wow. Never mentioned that. So I come to rehearsal completely unprepared, reading my lines from paper. 

The group using the practice room before us ran late and had the door locked. Then we got kicked out early because an instructor came by and said schedule be damned, he needed to use the room. 

The director couldn't / wouldn't schedule another practice. I said I wasn't comfortable doing the job without more practice. He told me there was nobody else to do the part, and I would just have to do my best. 

Presentation day. I get my first 2 lines out and then I couldn't remember a damn thing more. Had no idea what the play was even about or what my lines meant so I couldn't even fake it. After I missed my line, nobody else could remember theirs either. The director wasn't allowed to help. So we all just stood there paralyzed and embarrassed until the instructor called it a wash. 

I assume he got a pretty bad grade because he never spoke to me again.
